<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Sean McWhinnie, Oxford Research and Policy,_x000b_and Jan Peters, Katalytik (WSC065)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 60.55pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sean McWhinnie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, Oxford Research and Policy,</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Jan Peters</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Katalytik</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (WSC065)</span></h1><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Executive summary</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM and gender experts Jan Peters and Sean McWhinnie consider the successes of past measures to improve the retention and advancement of women in academic STEM roles. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Consideration is given to the impact of past measures, tendencies to reinvent the wheel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> strategic approach and positioning. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Key points covered are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The need for a long-term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">view and a strategic lead for gender in STEM from the national academies with clear input from the Research and Funding Councils;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Much work has already been</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> done in this area but much of the information generated is in the grey-literature and so not always easily accessible;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Athena SWAN scheme has the potential to address many of the barriers to the progression and retention of women in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">science, technolog</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y, engineering, mathematics and medicine (STEMM)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> through implementation of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> good working practices. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Better delivery of the Athena developed tools and a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ssured</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> funding for the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Athena </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">SWAN scheme is required;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Appreciation of d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iscipline differences and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the need to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">encourage learned societies to take a subject-view of their fields</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and in particular the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">need for greater engagement of the engineering professional institutions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Improvement in parental leave arrangements to reduce the impact on women’s career</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">normalise career breaks</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and support with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> part-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">time and flexible working;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The need to employ postdoctoral res</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">earchers on permanent contracts.</span></li></ul><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Introduction</span></h1><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Jan Peters and Sean McWhinnie have collaborated on several pieces of work around STEM and the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> STEM workforce over the last ten years exploring and making clear recommendations to stakeholders across a range of diversity dimensions but especially gender.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Jan Peters ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n academic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> then</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> industry based career before entering the science policy arena at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">NERC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">then </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">taking a secondment to DTI to run the women in science team</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in 1999</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Jan helped launch the Athena </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Project</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">established the Royal Society diversity programme and continues to s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it on several strategic STEM diversity groups including for Construction Skills, Royal Society of Chemistry </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(RSC) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institute of Physics</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(IOP) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> now runs a consultancy, Katalytik</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> specialising in STEM inclusion an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d engagement undertaking policy-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">based s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tudies and intervention programmes. She is a past President of the Women’s Engineering Society.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Sean McWhinnie has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">worked in academic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hemistry </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and for the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">RSC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> where, among other things, he established and led the RSC’s diversity programme.  Sean now runs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a consultancy, Oxford Research and Policy, which undertakes general policy work and analysis, including work relating to equality and diversity in STEMM, and in particular providing support to universities in the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Athena SWAN work.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Recent clients of Kat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">alytik and Oxford Research and Policy include the Royal Society, Royal Academy of Engineering, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL Engineering, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institute of Physics, London Mathematical Society, Royal Astronomical Society, University of Oxford, University of Cambridge, University of Kent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">University of Southampton, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">University of St Andrews, University of Manchester, University of Strathclyde, Kings College London, UK Resource Centre for Women in SET, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Vitae</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have collaborated on this submission because </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we share similar view on the i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ssues in question.</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span></h1><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The challenges faced by women in academia have been discussed many times over the last 15 years. One of the reasons why we </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">continually </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">find ourselves asking these </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">questions is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lack of a long-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">term sustainable strategy for interventions and monitoring progress</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In addition many initiatives have been established as peripheral to the STEM power base and decision making bodies.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who raised the issue of women in science in the UK at a policy level after the 1994 Science White Paper have since retired and their legacy, the Rising Tide Report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is out of print. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 31.1pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Much of the UK’s women in science effort was, until 2004, volunteer based. There is a limit on the time and energy that can be expended as a volunteer. Funded programmes between 2004 and 2012 have now ceased and the workforce dispersed. An impact of the way that UK policy in this area has evolved is a lack of corporate memory and continued introduction of similar schemes and ideas. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Initiatives tackling returning and re-entering STEM careers remain short-term and haven’t differentiated between the different needs of those returning to the same employer or to the labour force. Efforts from 2004 to 2011 were short-term and focused on confidence and basic skills rather than Master’s level technical skills.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Rising Tide report stimulated some small scale initiatives and an increase in voluntary groups. It was not until 1999 that the Promoting SET for Women Unit produced a strategic framework and set about encouraging the community to take a more strategic approach and began a more structured evidenced-based approach, tackling returners to STEM careers for the first time in a methodical way. The unit also published the first comprehensive UK web based dataset on women in STEM and a dashboard of data. This was revised by UKRC and in 2013 is being re-launched by Talent 2030.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Athena Project, launched in 1999, set out to stimulate small projects and promote good practice and innovations for two years before setting a strategic view. The best known legacies of the project are the Athena SWAN Charter and Awards. The good practice reports that the Project produced also remain and the Athena Forum, which was established to look after the Athena Project’s legacy, has produced some useful tools for academic career management. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many studies have examined the issues surrounding the leaky pipeline for women in STEM.  Reports have been published by Funding Councils and learned societies, like the RSC</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the IOP.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many of the reports on women in science have been published in the grey-literature and, despite efforts to collate and catalogue the literature by some, the community forgets still valid reports and guides such as the out of print and no longer available SHEFCE Winning Women series from 1998.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There has been comparatively little progress in university engineering departments in advancing women’s careers. In part this can be attributed to the way that the engineering professional institutions are set up and the large variation in the size of their membership bodies. We produced a report on Engineering Careers in 2013.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Royal Society and the Royal Academy of Engineering currently have a focus on diversity, but both have short-term funding from BIS for this work. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While the question here is the lack of progression of women in academic careers, the context of the proportions of women in undergraduate programmes and taking school qualifications should also be considered. The proportions of women at undergraduate level vary widely: 10-12% on mechanical engineering and electrical engineering courses; around 20% on undergraduate physics courses; around 45% on undergraduate chemistry courses; 60% on undergraduate biological science courses; 80% on psychology courses; and 90% on undergraduate nursing courses.  The proportion of undergraduates who are female suggest target proportions for females at all career levels.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The factors affecting the proportions of women on undergraduate courses are complex and vary from subject to subject.  Women are more likely than men to enter higher education: around 59% of those taking undergraduate courses in the UK are female, which means that the expected proportion of women on STEM courses is 59%. For many engineering courses and for physics, the proportions of women are limited by the proportions of females taking prerequisite courses at school. Women are more likely than men to choose to study the biological sciences, medicine and subjects allied to medicine.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Leakage of women occurs in the transition to postgraduate study and during postgraduate study. In many, but not all subjects, women are less likely than men to go onto postgraduate study choosing instead to seek employment; experiences during postgraduate study can affect an individual’s likelihood of staying in a STEM career. Also different subjects have different </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cultures in respect of the way research is carried out such as the organisation of people in research teams, publishing behaviours and the range of funding sources. All these factors affect men and women differently.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The vast majority of those who study STEM subjects do so because they are interested in their subject. An individual’s experience of full-time research as a PhD researcher, and their observations of principle investigators and post-doctoral researchers, affects their decisions as to whether or not to continue in STEM research. In other words, experience of the process of carrying out research, and observations on the careers of academic researchers, affects whether or not an individual is well disposed towards a research and/or an academic career.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While the proportions of women fall with increasing seniority, the reasons underlying the fall are not clear-cut, and often a number of factors combine to affect the progress of women. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We are aware that a number of institutions and other bodies will be submitting their views of the main reasons the proportion of women fall further up the academic career ladder. We attempt to summarise some of those reasons below but we will not go into great detail as we believe that many of these factors have been explored previously in a number of reports. Among the many reasons why women’s careers in STEM stall in comparison to men’s are:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The practice of employing post-doctoral researchers on short-term contracts which affects an individual’s entitlement to maternity leave and will affect the ability of an individual to get a mortgage, etc;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Uncertainly over the funding of, and arrangements for, maternity (parental) leave for postdoctoral researchers funded by grant income;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inadequate tailored career development opportunities for post-doctoral researchers and a reluctance on the part of some principle investigators to allow post-doctoral researchers some independence to develop their own research, including writing research proposals;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Poor arrangements for the induction of new academic staff and inadequate the start up support like funds and a studentship;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The cumulative disadvantage of delayed promotion, caused by, in general, women’s relative reluctance to put themselves forward, and inadequate support being provided to staff to prepare them for promotion;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The cultural norm for women to take principle caring responsibility, including taking maternity leave after child birth;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Dual career couples and the trailing spouse syndrome whereby the lower paid or less senior partner leaves a job and follows their partner, or, where a couple decides to sacrifice the female’s career in the expectation that the woman will take a career break to look after children and in consequence fall back in her career progression;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The “chilly climate” that can make women feel ‘out of the decision making loop’ or subject to subtle pressures and bullying;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inadequate general support to get individuals’ careers back on track following a career break including recognition of the limits on women’s ability to travel and attend conferences if they have childcare responsibilities and inadequate protection of research time;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Preferential assignment of pastoral caring roles to women and spending too much time on being the “token female” on committees;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inadequate experience of substantial committees or of financial management;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Disproportionate allocation of institutional resources and laboratory space</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (ref MIT survey);</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Likelihood that men in a department will have a more senior sponsor or advocate;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inadequate access to networks;</span></li></ol></ol></ol><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></h1><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM graduates move into a huge variety STEM and non-STEM roles and sectors.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The transition of scientifically trained people into a variety of non-STEM roles and sectors benefits the UK economy and enriches society.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">When surveyed the majority of both male and female STEM students, at all levels, state that they wish to use their STEM qualifications in their careers. Not all PhD level students necessarily want to work in research roles, and, in chemistry,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> where evidence is available, a lower proportion of women than men express a wish to work in research/technical roles. However, in molecular biosciences,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> similar proportions of men and women at PhD level express the desire to work in technical/research roles.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Data suggest that women are more likely than men to leave, or choose not to take up, STEM roles.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">When leaving undergraduate study the proportion of graduates that move directly into STEM roles varies from subject to subject.  More vocational subjects – like medicine, dentistry, or veterinary science –have higher proportions of graduates moving into STEM roles, than subjects in the physical or biological sciences, or engineering.  After undergraduate courses, reasonably large proportions of graduates from some subjects enter non-graduate level roles, presumably as a temporary measure.  However, research carried out for BIS suggests that those who take this path do not necessarily subsequently take STEM roles.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Much higher proportions of graduates from STEM postgraduate courses, and in particular from doctoral courses, than from STEM undergraduate courses, go into STEM roles and sectors.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The consequence of higher proportions of women than men moving out of STEM is that the UK economy is missing out on talent at a time when the future for the UK is in developing a high-tech economy.</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></h1><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Athena SWAN award scheme and the IOP’s Juno Project require monitoring and interrogation of key gender-disaggregated data and the implementation of good working practices covering the full career path of academics. Aspects of good practice cover all key areas including recruitment of staff, postdoctoral researchers, induction, training and development, appraisal, promotion, and support before, during and after career breaks.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many institutions have found that implementing good working practices benefits all staff, evidenced in research, whereas bad working practices tend to adversely affect women more than men. Consequently men support action implemented around the Athena SWAN scheme.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As well as learning about good practice from each other, institutions have available to them much material describing generic good practice that is available from the Athena Project,</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Athena Forum,</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the RSC,</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the IOP, the London Mathematical Society</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and from the Equality Challenge Unit, which currently hosts Athena SWAN.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Athena SWAN charter and awards were launched in 2005 and the first awards were given in 2006.  The numbers of submissions for awards rose steadily to around 80 in the academic year 2011-12 but a combination of increasing numbers of renewals and announcements from research funders on requirements to evidence action on women in science, has led to a significant increase in the number of submissions in 2012-13 (to about 200).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although the scheme has run for 8 years, mass participation is relatively recent.  In consequence significant changes in the numbers of women at senior level will not be evident for a number of years.  Where impact is evident is in improving working practices, and improved staff assessment of those practices.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For now, the success of Athena SWAN is best evidenced by its popularity (albeit some of that popularity has been stimulated by requirements of research funders) and by the improved </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">working practices in many STEM departments. That popularity does provide a significant challenge as Athena SWAN needs to scale up its operation in order to meet demand. The research funder requirements have also changed the nature of the award scheme from voluntary to, at least in the case of those seeking NHS funding, obligatory.  This in turn puts additional demands on Athena SWAN as the consequences of failure for some are serious. Notably this has diverted a focus in some institutions away from engineering.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Increasing numbers of institutions are making staff appointments specifically to support Athena SWAN work.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Daphne Jackson Fellowship programme is going from strength to strength and offering a good pathway for women with PhDs to restart their career. But it is still small scale and focused on a small community of highly qualified women.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We believe that universities should:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Resource and undertake work to implement good working practices across all STEM departments. The model for that good practice should be taken from the Athena SWAN charter. Ideally institutions and departments will apply successfully for Athena SWAN awards but the strategic aim must be to implement good working practices for all staff and thereby to improve the recruitment, retention and progression of females within the STEMM disciplines. The focus should not be merely to gain Athena SWAN awards. Gaining of awards should be seen as recognition of and accreditation for the good practice in place;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities should employ postdoctoral researchers on permanent contracts;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities should allow those returning from career breaks an automatic right to flexibility in their working arrangements for a period of time, including the possibility of part-time working with a guaranteed right to return to full-time working withn a set period of time;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research funders should ensure that additional funding is always provided for postdoctoral researchers who take parental leave, and that the duration of the grant is adjusted to take account of time spent on parental leave;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research funders should maintain and extend their requirements for recipients of funding to evidence action on women in STEMM;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research funders should publicise more widely that spending on Athena SWAN activities is an allowable research overhead;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research funders in general, and the Research Councils in particular, should provide funding for Athena SWAN but also discuss with Athena SWAN ways of providing other support such as staff to oversee awards panels, and general administrative support;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:110%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 61.7pt; padding-left:23.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities and research funders should provide a wider range of fellowship funding options to help couples manage dual careers.</span></li></ol></ol></ol><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:80%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></h1><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The cultural convention that women should take parental leave following the birth of a child adversely affects women’s careers disproportionately. Whenever discussions of extending paternity leave rights are held many complaints are voiced by “business” in general and SMEs in particular that the costs of parental leave will cause untold damage. However, at present the public sector bears much of the cost of parental leave as many female dominated professions are in found in the public sector, e.g., teaching, nursing, etc.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government should act to drive forward shared parental leave for all couples. A mechanisms must be provided to allow dual career couples to split parental leave however they wish.  The administrative burden of such a system is worth it as it will no longer be necessary for women to feel obliged to put their careers on hold, or even to sacrifice their careers if they have a child.  We do not support a system of enforced shared parental leave - couples should be free to choose.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government should ensure that Athena SWAN has adequate funding so that the good work stimulated by Athena SWAN is maintained and extended.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A long-term strategic view of the scale of the issue is needed, supported by long-term dedicated funding. This was identified in the Greenfield Set Fair</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">report. This strategic view needs to be driven from the national academies of science and engineering with support from the Research and Funding Council</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s and not delivered through a commercial “target-based” contract </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">such as how</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Greenfield recommendations were delivered. The participation of women in research is far too important.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should strongly encourage learned societies to take a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">subject-view of their fields</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. In particular, engineering-related professional bodies to look more closely at the sectors in which they operate to understand cultures and careers in both industry and academia and stimulate new career pathways and training t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">o help professionals transition between industry and academia as well as to help women (and men) better manage career and caring responsibilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">The Rising Tide: Report on Women in Science, Engineering and Technology, Engineering &amp; Technology Committee on Women in Science</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">, 1994</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Factors Affecting the Career Choices of Graduate Chemists, Royal Society of Chemistry, London, 2000 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">http://www.rsc.org/images/Factors%20Affecting%20the%20Career%20Choices%20of%20Graduate%20Chemists_tcm18-12806.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">); Recruitment and Retention of Women in Academic Chemistry, Royal Society of Chemistry, London, 2003 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">http://www.rsc.org/images/Recruitment%20and%20Retention%20of%20Women%20in%20Academic%20Chemistry_tcm18-12807.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">Women in University Physics Departments: A Site Visit Scheme 2003–2005, Institute of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">Physics, London, 2006 (http://www.iop.org/publications/iop/archive/file_42616.pdf)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Winning Women 